But enough of that.  <br>
<br>
I find it amusing that you cannot let go of your preconceived ideas about religion and religious terms.  First of all, let's go over some terms.  These are the definitions as used by much of the wiccan community.<br>
Magic is the practice of slight of hand often used by stage performers from Harry Houdini to Sigfreid and Roy.<br>
Magick is the use of ancient knowledge to aid in the improvement of one's life.  Magick has three sub-divisions.  High magick is the practice of invoking spirits as a means of achieving some ends.  Obviously high magick uses the supernatural.  Low magick is the manipulation of energy fields to achieve some change in the surrounding environment.  This may include anything from trying to change someone's luck by holding a stone which vibrates at a different frequency than the person does, to an old fashioned rain dance.  Some parts of low magick require the supernatural.  Kitchen magick is the use of herbs, oils and spices to effect change in the physical body of an individual.  This practice later coined the term 'pharmacology.  However, as society advances more towards 'modern medicine' the wiccan with his/her kitchen magick chooses to continue using all natural ingredients believing them to be more potent.(and usually being right)<br>
Oh and so that you aren't wondering, here's the dictionary.com definition.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>An action or effort undertaken because of a personal need to effect change, especially as associated with Wicca or Wiccan beliefs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Source: The American HeritageÂ® Dictionary of the English Language, Fourth Edition<br>
Copyright Â© 2000 by Houghton Mifflin Company.<br>
Published by Houghton Mifflin Company. All rights reserved.<br>
